items.title:
From this
    <code>try {
      MealExpenses expenses = expenseReportDAO.getMeals(employee.getID());
      m_total += expenses.getTotal();
    } catch (MealExpensesNotFound e) {
      m_total += getMealPerDiem();
    }</code>
      to this
      <code>MealExpenses expenses = expenseReportDAO.getMeals(employee.getID());
      m_total += expenses.getTotal();</code>
<code>public class PerDiemMealExpenses implements MealExpenses {
        public int getTotal() {
          // return the per diem default
        }
      }</code>

If you pass null, then the callee has to always check for null args.
    <code>public double xProjection(Point p1, Point p2) {
      if (p1 == null || p2 == null) {
         throw InvalidArgumentException(
           "Invalid argument for MetricsCalculator.xProjection");
      }
      return (p2.x – p1.x) * 1.5;
    }</code>
    a cleaner way to do this could be
    <code>public double xProjection(Point p1, Point p2) {
       assert p1 != null : "p1 should not be null";
       assert p2 != null : "p2 should not be null";
       return (p2.x – p1.x) * 1.5;
    }</code>
    But this also doesn't solve the problem, instead of <code>NullPointerException</code> we are going to get some different <code>RuntimeException</code>
